Ivan V7/21/2022, 9:54:41 AM

Good Morning Jerry Everything's fine by the way. Just letting you know I finally worked out why the Google Maps API marker icons are so laggy... believe it or not... every single time you hover over a marker, the API fetches the URL for the icon svg image. Worse yet, this behaviour cannot be avoided even if we use a .png image which normally would be cached by the browser. The API doesn't care. Every time we issue the marker.setIcon command the API redraws the marker's object image, and it sends out another URL hit for the svg file!

jerryL7/21/2022, 9:56:36 AM

hmm should probably avoid doing url hit when hover on marker.

Ivan V7/21/2022, 10:00:41 AM

Yes, agreed. Worse yet, every time we click on the icon it sends a lat/long update hit to the server, but that's another issue I'll be solving today. But you're right - this is one of those moments where we might have to say "Sorry Boss but this is out of our hands, we can't stop the Google Maps API from acting this way... we're better off using Google's inbuilt icons." Think about it, by default the "Place Visit Points" program shows All Levels until a user chooses a specific level. If we're dealing with a building that has 50 levels with an average of 25 beacons per level, that's 750 URL hits the Google Maps API makes just to draw our custom icons. No wonder it's so slow sometimes to draw itself!

Ivan V10/18/2022, 1:36:11 PMEdited 10/18/2022, 1:38:21 PM

In short, it's impossible to move jQuery dialogs into the main mapObj until AFTER a mapObj has fully instantiated itself. The timeline for when a mapObj fully instantiates itself is independant of when the jQuery dialogs get instantiated. Refer to the attached screenshots. The mapObj follows it's own load timeline, which is separate to the Google Maps API being loaded. Currently, the Google Maps API does NOT provide a callback event which can be called once (and once only) AFTER the mapOBJ is fully instantiated. If it did, that's where I would put the call to create the jQuery dialogs AND that's where I would use your suggested code. The API does provide an "idle" event however, and that event occurs every time the mapObj finishes changing, including AFTER the mapObj gets fully instantiated. So for now, that's where I've placed the minMaxObjects() function. My solution works because it allows the jQuery dialogs AND the mapObj to instantiate themselves following their own timelines, but it still moves the dialogs into the mapObj too. Please Remember: It's not ONLY the jQuery dialogs that I have to move. I also have to move the side bar panels and other html elements too.

So I'm comfortable using DataTables.net, I've used it extensively in the past but it DOES want to take complete control of the JSON fetches, and it can be tedious to implement (which is a barrier to entry). ivanv07051/3/2023, 10:02:19 AM

So my opinion, given that I'm doing the traffic cop role is this.... JIRA still has so many imperfections I sometimes want to throw a brick at my computer screen! LOL But the reality is we have to work with what we've got. And in fairness to you.... we did a massive HUGE migration of tasks and epics in the week before Christsmas so it hasn't been easy. So.... hurdle (1) JIRA allows us to slide Issues into a Sprint but not sub-tasks. Therefore we're forced to deal with Issues within Epics, rather than sub-tasks within Issues. Hurdle (2) JIRA allows us to re-order sub-tasks chronologically within Issues but it doesn't "easily" allow us to re-order Issues within Epics. It can be done, but the process is not elegant. Hurdle (3) JIRA doesn't easily allow us to find tasks which may have slipped through the net in a given sprint as "not started". Hence, given all these issues... my advice would be, create Sprints which are two weeks long and let me really work on Issues being truly "Sprint Ready" before we put them in a sprint. Next, I reckon you should only plan a Sprint up to 70-80% full, which in turn will allow us to be reactive during a Sprint with regards to adding new Job Tickets.

AR_TRAN does... but not AR_MAST. AR_TRAN keeps the individual items (and details) which are purchased, AR_MAST keeps the consolidated summary figures.

ivanv07052/15/2023, 3:05:51 PMEdited 2/15/2023, 3:56:01 PM

GOOD NEWS! Reece helped me solve the problem... Firstly, the problem has nothing to do with db version thankfully. It's a problem caused by the global SHOW_PERMISSION_GROUPS setting. In my case, my local site_settings.py file was setting my SHOW_PERMISSION_GROUPS to equal false. I don't why... somebody in the past entered that setting and prior to today I had never once realised it's importance. So what was happening is the edit_visit_point.html file was only producing the permissions data IF the SHOW_PERMISSION_GROUPS was true. Hence, when I tried to save my Visit Point data, the back end was failing to see the required data.
